{
  "text": "Acute kidney injury (AKI) is a common complication that increases the risk of poor graft outcome in patients undergoing kidney transplantation (KT). Kidney grafts seem to be vulnerable to poor early function recovery because of various types of acute perioperative damage, such as ischemia-reperfusion injury, immunological insult, medication toxicity, and surgical stress [CITATION_1] . In living-donor kidney transplantation (LDKT), better graft quality and patient condition result in better early graft function compared with deceased-donor KT. However, the reported incidence of poor early graft function after LDKT is 10-20%, and this early graft dysfunction is closely related closely to an increased risk of long-term graft failure [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] .",
